zenwebp ARM (aarch64) bench unblock — 2026-05-30
================================================

Host:        Hetzner cax21, aarch64 Ampere/Neoverse-N1, 4 cores, 7.5 GB RAM
Base commit: zenwebp main@origin fe4102ab7cfb (at time of work)
Toolchain:   cargo 1.96.0, rustc stable, edition 2024

WHAT WAS DELIVERED AND VERIFIED
-------------------------------
Bench unblock (the baseline blocker): every zenwebp bench resolved the corpus
through a hardcoded default "/home/lilith/work/codec-corpus" that exists on no
CI/dev runner — so encode_benchmark / encode_vs_libwebp panicked out-of-the-box,
and the decode benches silently skipped every image.

Fix shipped: benches/encode_benchmark.rs and benches/encode_vs_libwebp.rs now
resolve the corpus root in the same order the codec-corpus crate uses:
  1. CODEC_CORPUS_DIR  (explicit override)
  2. CODEC_CORPUS_CACHE/codec-corpus/v1  (the crate's cache env var)
  3. $HOME/.cache/codec-corpus/v1        (the crate's default cache location)
No private codec-corpus internals are touched (Corpus.root is private; the path
is reconstructed via the crate's documented {cache}/codec-corpus/v{MAJOR} layout,
confirmed in codec-corpus 1.1.0 source). Plus dev/arm_profile.rs — a perf-friendly
encode+decode profiling driver (gated behind the existing `_profiling` feature).

DIRECTLY VERIFIED (tool output I saw and can stand behind):
  - cargo build --release --benches                                   -> compiles
  - cargo build --release --features _profiling --example arm_profile -> compiles
  - cargo test --release --lib                                        -> 257 passed, 0 failed
  (no codec source changed, so encode/decode output is byte-identical to base by
   construction.)

HONEST-STOP on the perf numbers
-------------------------------
The SSH channel to the ARM box degraded repeatedly during this session. I could
NOT cleanly re-trace the exact per-symbol perf percentages or the wall-clock
ms/decode figures to a single verified run on the committed arm_profile.rs.
Per the no-fabricated-benchmarks rule, those unverified numbers were removed
rather than shipped as if measured (see the .tsv for the re-run recipe). The
structural finding — every vectorizable hot kernel is already archmage NEON on
aarch64 — comes from source inspection, not from a fabricated perf %.

OUTCOME: bench UNBLOCKED + profiling tool shipped; no source perf change (no
measured ARM win available and none could be verified this session).
